For anyone in need an explanation:
What he's talking about with correlation doesn't equal causation basically means just because and intelligent person does these things, and it's shown that intelligent people have this in common, it doesn't mean that intelligence is the cause of aforementioned thing.
E.g
When he says that studies show that smarter people don't smoke, that means that smart people not smoking is common, but neither is the cause of the other, there is a correlation ( common connection) but there is a third factor that is the causation. I.e there may be someone with low intelligence who smokes, but they have a really stressful life, which is the cause of their smoking.

The phrase correlation =/= causation annoys me. It should really say that correlation doesn’t PROVE causation. It’s a mistake to assume that correlation is irrelevant, because things that are highly correlated are often (not always) a hint that there’s something causal at play, just maybe in an unexpected way.

Things that are causal by definition are correlated as well, so to say there’s no relationship between the two is false.

Okay but they’re actually just wrong though. There was no “gotcha” moment. Just because correlation does not mean causation, doesn’t mean that correlation is not correlation. As in, you’re more likely to be smart if you do those things. Where it breaks down is that you shouldn’t change your behavior in order to be more smart. That’s the only way the misunderstanding could apply. What they may have been trying to say is that there are other indicators that are much more highly correlated with how smart you are that you should be weighing MORE, such as iq tests, other people's perspectives of you, how easily you learn new concepts, etc. (Again, mixing up correlation and causation with these factors might be trying to get other people to think you’re smart to become smarter.) Implying “this doesn’t matter because correlation doesn’t equal causation” is kind of sad, because it shows they don’t actually have a good enough grasp of the scientific method, or what that saying even means

Which eventually can hurt people. Like the orthodontic industry which pull teeth for aesthetic reasons. They get more space for the teeth to move which makes their job easier and easier to get that smile. They don’t tell you anything about the possible dangerous consequences of pulling healthy premolars and then retracting the palate/jaw (which also is difficult to reverse if something wrong happens, than say just expanding the palate to correct the wrong bite (which is much easier to reverse)). The consequences can be, reduced tongue space, neck and jaw pain, sleep apnea, TMD, tinnitus, etc.) They simply deny that they can make the jaw/palate smaller which is utterly wrong.

If people have heard of falsification in science, it’s about that we never can deny anomalies that occurs.

It is there to make sure to constantly evolve science because we can never know whether a hypothesis or theory is completely true, partially true or completely untrue. Only time will tell.

Falsification is today an important concept in the philosophy of science, especially in Karl Popper, who argues that there is a significant asymmetry between falsification and verification when it comes to general statements and natural laws. A complete verification of natural laws is impossible if they (simplified) have the logical structure "All A has the property E".

On the other hand, it is in principle logically possible to falsify them: the statement "All ravens are black" is in principle falsified if we find a non-black raven, even though all the ravens we have seen so far are black, we can not know that it never have been, or will emerge, ravens that are not black.

For Popper and his followers, it therefore becomes a methodological principle in all science to increase the degree of falsifiability. A law or generalization (theory, hypothesis) that resists attempts at falsification thereby increases its acceptability or credibility. The more effectively we search for falsification or falsification opportunities, the more effectively we also promote the growth of knowledge.

There are countless patterns in nature and many patterns that will agree with a hypothesis even if it is not necessarily true. Therefore, it also means that it is very easy to generate false positive data in scientific research whether it is conscious or unconscious. After all, it is people who conduct the research. Much of what I say here actually supports the "correlation does not equal causation" argument. But the problem with that argument is that it can be used against its purpose by authoritarian people. There is a large amount of corruption most people do not know about. And money is very often the root of such actions.
